            <head>254. Editorial Note</head>
            <p>On December 10, 1987, President <persName corresp="rec5PPNCl6qqfgBAq">Ronald
                    Reagan</persName> hosted Soviet General Secretary <persName
                    corresp="recXTrNyt2vU9QpAl">Mikhail Gorbachev</persName> in a noon meeting in
                the White House Oval Office followed by a working luncheon in the Family Dining Room
                that lasted until 2:10 p.m. “After initial pleasantries,” President <persName
                    corresp="rec5PPNCl6qqfgBAq">Reagan</persName> “opened by saying that he’d had a
                chance to review the joint statement,” and “understood that working delegations were
                now focused on the <gloss target="#t_START_1">
                    <rs type="event" corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O">START</rs>
                </gloss> and <rs type="event" corresp="rec0rc9kDG6TIF88N">Defense and Space</rs>
                portions of the statement, and suggested that we get a report.” <persName
                    corresp="recXTrNyt2vU9QpAl">Gorbachev</persName> replied that “meetings were now
                in progress between Marshal <persName corresp="recIjriLJ5q37CiAe"
                    >Akhromeyev</persName> and Mr. <persName corresp="recZmD7Wil34KIjtu"
                    >Nitze</persName>,” and that while they were working “he and <persName
                    corresp="rec5PPNCl6qqfgBAq">the President</persName> could have some further
                decisions of <rs type="topic" corresp="rec7XCpI38AIhVpLJ">regional issues</rs>.”
                    <persName corresp="rec5PPNCl6qqfgBAq">The President</persName> agreed.
                (Memorandum of Conversation, December 10, 1987; [Department of State, Executive
                Secretariat, S/S-IRM Records, Memoranda of <pb facs="1166" n="1139" xml:id="pg_1139"
                /> Conversations Pertaining to United States and <gloss target="#t_USSR_1"
                    >USSR</gloss> Relations, 1981–1990, Lot 93D188, Washington Summit, 12/87]) The
                memoranda of their conversations are printed in <ref target="frus1981-88v06#d114">
                    <hi rendition="simple_italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1981–1988, vol. VI, Soviet
                    Union, October 1986–January 1989, Documents 114</ref>–<ref
                    target="frus1981-88v06#d115">115</ref>.</p>
